### Method Overriding in Kotlin

Overriding allows a subclass to provide a specific implementation of a function or property defined in its superclass.

---

### Override Keyword

Use `override` to replace a superclass member.

```kotlin
open class Animal {
    open fun makeSound() = println("Animal sound")
}

class Dog : Animal() {
    override fun makeSound() = println("Bark!")
}
```

---

### Overriding Properties

Properties can also be overridden.

```kotlin
open class Shape {
    open val area: Double get() = 0.0
}

class Circle(val radius: Double) : Shape() {
    override val area: Double get() = Math.PI * radius * radius
}

class Square(val side: Double) : Shape() {
    override val area: Double get() = side * side
}
```

---

### Override Rules

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Member must be `open` | Cannot override a `final` member |
| Signature must match | Same name and parameters |
| Return type must be covariant | Subtype of original return type |
| Visibility cannot be reduced | e.g., `protected` cannot become `private` |

---

### Calling Super Implementation

```kotlin
open class Parent {
    open fun greet() = println("Hello from parent")
}

class Child : Parent() {
    override fun greet() {
        super.greet()  // Call parent implementation
        println("Hello from child")
    }
}
```

---

### Multiple Inheritance of Implementation

Kotlin supports multiple interface inheritance. Use `super<Interface>` to specify which implementation to call.

```kotlin
interface A {
    fun doSomething() = println("A")
}

interface B {
    fun doSomething() = println("B")
}

class C : A, B {
    override fun doSomething() {
        super<A>.doSomething()
        super<B>.doSomething()
    }
}
```

---

### Preventing Further Override

Mark overridden members as `final` to stop further overriding.

```kotlin
open class Parent {
    open fun method() {}
}

open class Child : Parent() {
    final override fun method() {}  // Cannot be overridden further
}

class GrandChild : Child() {
    // override fun method() {}  // Error: final
}
```

> **Key Point:** Always use the `override` modifier. It is required (not optional) in Kotlin, preventing accidental overrides.

codeExample:
open class Employee(val name: String) {
    open fun calculateBonus(): Double = 0.0
    open fun work() = println("$name is working")
}

class Manager(name: String, val teamSize: Int) : Employee(name) {
    override fun calculateBonus(): Double = 5000.0 * teamSize
    override fun work() {
        super.work()
        println("$name manages $teamSize people")
    }
}

fun main() {
    val emp = Employee("Alice")
    val mgr = Manager("Bob", 5)

    println("${emp.name} bonus: ${emp.calculateBonus()}")
    println("${mgr.name} bonus: ${mgr.calculateBonus()}")
    mgr.work()
}
